1) Electric Charge

There are two types of electric charge: positive and negative.
Inside an atom, there are negatively charged electrons, positively charged protons, and neutral (no charge) neutrons.
Atoms contain equal numbers of protons and electrons as they have equal and opposite charges.
These charges cancel out so the overall charge of an atom is zero.
Opposite charges attract, like charges repel.
Whether two objects attract or repel depends on their charge:
If the charges are the opposite, they will attract.
If the charges are the same, they will repel.
Attraction or repulsion summary table (positive/positive → repel; positive/negative → attract; negative/positive → attract; negative/negative → repel).
Extended tier only — Electric charge is measured in units called coulombs (C).
Examiner Tips and Tricks: Remember “opposites attract”; don’t confuse electrostatic forces with magnetic forces.
  1. There are two types of electric charge: positive and negative.
  2. Inside an atom, there are negatively charged electrons, positively charged protons, and neutral (no charge) neutrons.
  3. Atoms contain equal numbers of protons and electrons as they have equal and opposite charges.
  4. These charges cancel out so the overall charge of an atom is zero.
  5. Opposite charges attract, like charges repel.
  6. Whether two objects attract or repel depends on their charge:
  7. If the charges are the opposite, they will attract.
  8. If the charges are the same, they will repel.
  9. Attraction or repulsion summary table (positive/positive → repel; positive/negative → attract; negative/positive → attract; negative/negative → repel).

2) Demonstrating Electric Charges

Charging by friction: when certain insulating solids are rubbed against each other, they can become electrically charged.
The charges remain on the insulators and cannot immediately flow away.
One gains a net positive charge and the other gains a net negative charge.
A polythene rod may be given a charge by rubbing it with a cloth; electrons are transferred away from the cloth to the rod.
The cloth has lost electrons so it becomes positively charged; the polythene rod has gained electrons so it becomes negatively charged.
With an acetate rod rubbed with a cloth, electrons are transferred away from the acetate rod to the cloth; the acetate becomes positively charged.
Experiment 1: investigating electrostatic charging by friction — aim: investigate how insulating materials can be charged by friction.
Variables: Independent = rods of different material; Dependent = charge on the rod; Control = time spent rubbing, same type of cloth, same length of rod.
Equipment: polythene rod; rods of different materials (acrylic, acetate, glass, wood); cloths; cradle; nylon string; wooden stand.
Method: (1) Rub polythene rod with cloth. (2) Suspend without touching ends. (3) Charge a second rod. (4) Bring it close. (5) Record whether attracted/repelled. (6) Repeat for different materials.
Example results table (charged material 1 vs charged material 2 vs attracted or repelled).
Analysis of results: electrons transferred to polythene → negative; electrons removed from acetate → positive.
If repelled by polythene, the materials have the same charge; if attracted, opposite charges.
Evaluating: reduce drafts; don’t touch charged ends; longer rubbing → more charge (keep time same).
Experiment 2: detecting charge using a gold-leaf electroscope — aim: detect charge using a gold leaf electroscope.
Variables: Independent = rods of different material; Dependent = charge on the rod.
Equipment: gold-leaf electroscope; polythene and acetate rods/strips; cloths.
Method: (1) Discharge plate by touch (leaf down). (2) Charge polythene. (3) Bring near plate and observe. (4) Move away and observe. (5) Touch plate and observe. (6) Repeat with acetate.
Example results table (charged material, action, gold leaf rises or falls, movement of electrons).
Analysis: Near plate — leaf rises. Negative polythene repels electrons down stem and leaf (they become negative and repel); positive acetate attracts electrons to plate (stem and leaf become positive and repel).
Move away — leaf falls; charges redistribute; stem and leaf neutral.
Touch plate — leaf stays risen; charge transferred to plate and down stem/leaf; electroscope charged.
Touch with finger — leaf falls; charge to earth; electroscope discharged.
Evaluating: don’t touch charged rod ends; if contact charging fails, press harder and draw rod along edge.
Examiner Tips and Tricks: demonstrations are observations; state a conclusion when describing a demo.

3) Electric Fields

Extended tier only — An electric field is a region of space in which an electric charge experiences a force.
The direction of the field at a point is the direction of force on a positive charge there.
Charged objects create electric fields around themselves (similar to magnets and magnetic fields).
An electric field is a vector quantity (magnitude and direction).
Electric field lines represent direction and magnitude; always directed from positive to negative.
Point charge: if positive, field lines radially outwards; if negative, radially inwards.
Charged conducting sphere: similar to point charge; charges distribute evenly; field lines perpendicular to surface.
Van de Graaff generator demonstrates the pattern.
Between two parallel plates: uniform field — lines are straight, parallel, equally spaced, from positive plate to negative plate.
  1. Extended tier only — An electric field is a region of space in which an electric charge experiences a force.
  2. The direction of the field at a point is the direction of force on a positive charge there.
  3. Charged objects create electric fields around themselves (similar to magnets and magnetic fields).
  4. An electric field is a vector quantity (magnitude and direction).
  5. Electric field lines represent direction and magnitude; always directed from positive to negative.
  6. Point charge: if positive, field lines radially outwards; if negative, radially inwards.
  7. Charged conducting sphere: similar to point charge; charges distribute evenly; field lines perpendicular to surface.
  8. Van de Graaff generator demonstrates the pattern.
  9. Between two parallel plates: uniform field — lines are straight, parallel, equally spaced, from positive plate to negative plate.

4) Investigating Conductors & Insulators

Conductors: allow charge (usually electrons) to flow easily — examples: silver, copper, aluminium, steel (metals).
Metallic conductors: positively charged metal ions with delocalised electrons (free to move); current is the rate of flow of electrons.
Insulators: have no free charges — examples: rubber, plastic, glass, wood. Some non‑metals allow a little static conduction.
Investigating with an electroscope — Aim: distinguish between good and bad conductors using a gold‑leaf electroscope.
Variables: Independent = different materials; Dependent = electrical conductivity of materials.
Equipment: gold‑leaf electroscope; polythene rod; cloth; different conducting and insulating materials (metal, plastic, glass, wood).
Method: (1) Discharge plate. (2) Charge polythene by friction. (3) Charge electroscope by contact (leaf stays up). (4) Touch test object to plate and observe. (5) Repeat for different materials.
Example results table (material vs gold leaf falls quickly or slowly vs good or bad conductor).
Analysis: good conductors → leaf falls quickly; poor conductors → leaf falls slowly; if no movement → good insulator. Expected: metals & graphite good; plastic, glass, wood, rubber, fabric poor/insulators.
Evaluating: use an electrometer for numerical comparisons.
  1. Conductors: allow charge (usually electrons) to flow easily — examples: silver, copper, aluminium, steel (metals).
  2. Metallic conductors: positively charged metal ions with delocalised electrons (free to move); current is the rate of flow of electrons.
  3. Insulators: have no free charges — examples: rubber, plastic, glass, wood. Some non‑metals allow a little static conduction.
  4. Investigating with an electroscope — Aim: distinguish between good and bad conductors using a gold‑leaf electroscope.
  5. Variables: Independent = different materials; Dependent = electrical conductivity of materials.
  6. Equipment: gold‑leaf electroscope; polythene rod; cloth; different conducting and insulating materials (metal, plastic, glass, wood).
  7. Method: (1) Discharge plate. (2) Charge polythene by friction. (3) Charge electroscope by contact (leaf stays up). (4) Touch test object to plate and observe. (5) Repeat for different materials.
  8. Example results table (material vs gold leaf falls quickly or slowly vs good or bad conductor).

  10. Evaluating: use an electrometer for numerical comparisons.

5) Current

Electric current is the rate of flow of electric charge.
Current flows when a circuit is formed (a wire connects the cell’s oppositely charged terminals).
By definition, conventional current flows from the positive terminal to the negative terminal; electrons flow in the opposite direction.
Measuring current: ammeters in series with the component.
Ammeters can be digital (electronic read‑out) or analogue (needle and scale).
Analogue ammeters: typical ranges 0.1–1.0A and 1.0–5.0A; check for zero error; avoid parallax by viewing perpendicularly.
Digital ammeters: can measure mA or μA; more precise; may flicker; check for zero error and correct for it.
Electrical conduction in metals: current is a flow of negatively charged electrons through a lattice of metal ions.
Extended tier only — I = Q / t, with I in A, Q in C, t in s; 1A = 1C/s.
Formula triangle (charge‑current‑time) and Worked Example conclusion: option B (4C in 0.5s gives 8A).
Extended tier only — Conventional current vs electron flow diagram: conventional +→−; electrons −→+.
Examiner Tips and Tricks: unit prefixes (mA); use triangles to rearrange, not as final answers; see speed/distance/time note.
  1. Electric current is the rate of flow of electric charge.
  2. Current flows when a circuit is formed (a wire connects the cell’s oppositely charged terminals).
  3. By definition, conventional current flows from the positive terminal to the negative terminal; electrons flow in the opposite direction.
  4. Measuring current: ammeters in series with the component.
  5. Ammeters can be digital (electronic read‑out) or analogue (needle and scale).
  6. Analogue ammeters: typical ranges 0.1–1.0A and 1.0–5.0A; check for zero error; avoid parallax by viewing perpendicularly.
  7. Digital ammeters: can measure mA or μA; more precise; may flicker; check for zero error and correct for it.
  8. Electrical conduction in metals: current is a flow of negatively charged electrons through a lattice of metal ions.
  9. Extended tier only — I = Q / t, with I in A, Q in C, t in s; 1A = 1C/s.
  10. Formula triangle (charge‑current‑time) and Worked Example conclusion: option B (4C in 0.5s gives 8A).
  11. Extended tier only — Conventional current vs electron flow diagram: conventional +→−; electrons −→+.
  12. Examiner Tips and Tricks: unit prefixes (mA); use triangles to rearrange, not as final answers; see speed/distance/time note.

Worked Example — When does 8A flow in a circuit?

  1. Use Q = I × t and rearrange to I = Q / t.
  2. Try the option with Q = 4C and t = 0.5s: I = 4 / 0.5 = 8A.
  3. Therefore that option is correct; other options give incorrect values for I.

6) Direct & Alternating Current

There are two types of current: direct current (d.c.) and alternating current (a.c.).
d.c.: steady current in one direction from positive to negative; cells/batteries produce d.c.; potential difference travels in one direction only.
a.c.: current continuously changes direction; supply terminals swap polarity; frequency = number of direction changes per second.
UK mains ≈ 230V, 50Hz.
Graphs: d.c. is a flat line; a.c. is sinusoidal.
Table comparing d.c. and a.c.: continuous in one direction vs constantly changing; produced by cells/batteries vs generators (mains); positive/negative terminal vs two identical terminals.
Examiner Tips and Tricks: sketch and label the graphs to explain differences.
  1. There are two types of current: direct current (d.c.) and alternating current (a.c.).
  2. d.c.: steady current in one direction from positive to negative; cells/batteries produce d.c.; potential difference travels in one direction only.
  3. a.c.: current continuously changes direction; supply terminals swap polarity; frequency = number of direction changes per second.
  4. UK mains ≈ 230V, 50Hz.
  5. Graphs: d.c. is a flat line; a.c. is sinusoidal.
  6. Table comparing d.c. and a.c.: continuous in one direction vs constantly changing; produced by cells/batteries vs generators (mains); positive/negative terminal vs two identical terminals.
  7. Examiner Tips and Tricks: sketch and label the graphs to explain differences.

7) Electromotive Force

Electromotive force (e.m.f.) is the potential difference of the power source in a circuit.
Definition: the electrical work done by a source in moving a unit charge around a complete circuit.
Measured in volts (V).
Extended tier only — E = W / Q (E in V, W in J, Q in C).
This should be compared to the definition of potential difference.
  1. Electromotive force (e.m.f.) is the potential difference of the power source in a circuit.
  2. Definition: the electrical work done by a source in moving a unit charge around a complete circuit.
  3. Measured in volts (V).
  4. Extended tier only — E = W / Q (E in V, W in J, Q in C).
  5. This should be compared to the definition of potential difference.

8) Potential Difference

Potential difference is the work done by a unit charge passing through a component.
Measured in volts (V); relates to energy transferred between two points.
Example: with a 12V cell, each coulomb gains 12J at the cell and loses 12J across components.
Measuring p.d.: voltmeter in parallel between two points; digital or analogue.
Analogue voltmeters: parallax error; typical ranges 0.1–1.0V and 0–5.0V; check zero error.
Digital voltmeters: can measure mV or μV; more precise; may flicker; check zero error.
Extended tier only — V = W / Q; one volt = 1J/C; energy equation W = V × Q.
Worked Example: Lamp 6V, Q = 4200C → W = 25 200J.
Examiner Tips and Tricks: connect voltmeter last; voltage vs potential difference wording; voltmeter connects across two points.
  1. Potential difference is the work done by a unit charge passing through a component.
  2. Measured in volts (V); relates to energy transferred between two points.
  3. Example: with a 12V cell, each coulomb gains 12J at the cell and loses 12J across components.
  4. Measuring p.d.: voltmeter in parallel between two points; digital or analogue.
  5. Analogue voltmeters: parallax error; typical ranges 0.1–1.0V and 0–5.0V; check zero error.
  6. Digital voltmeters: can measure mV or μV; more precise; may flicker; check zero error.
  7. Extended tier only — V = W / Q; one volt = 1J/C; energy equation W = V × Q.
  8. Worked Example: Lamp 6V, Q = 4200C → W = 25 200J.
  9. Examiner Tips and Tricks: connect voltmeter last; voltage vs potential difference wording; voltmeter connects across two points.

Worked Example — Energy transferred in a 6V lamp when 4200C flows

  1. From V = W / Q we have W = V × Q.
  2. Substitute V = 6V and Q = 4200C → W = 25 200J.

9) Resistance

Resistance is the opposition to current.
Free electrons collide with metal ions; higher resistance → lower current.
Good conductors have low resistance; insulators high resistance; adding resistors increases total R; wires and components have resistance (wires & batteries often taken as negligible in exams).
Ohm’s law: R = V / I; consequences — for constant p.d., increasing R decreases I; for constant I, increasing R increases p.d.
Worked Example: 12Ω and 0.3A → V = 3.6V.
Extended tier only — I‑V graphs: linear (ohmic) straight line through origin with constant R (wires, fixed resistors at constant temperature).
Non‑linear (non‑ohmic) curves (filament lamp, diode, LDRs, thermistors).
Filament lamp: as current increases, temperature and R increase; S‑shaped curve; flatter slope means higher R (increased lattice vibration impedes electrons).
Diode: conducts in one direction (forward bias) and not in reverse (reverse bias) — I‑V shows sharp increase forward, zero reverse.
Examiner Tips and Tricks: recognise, sketch, explain the three I‑V graphs.
  1. Resistance is the opposition to current.
  2. Free electrons collide with metal ions; higher resistance → lower current.
  3. Good conductors have low resistance; insulators high resistance; adding resistors increases total R; wires and components have resistance (wires & batteries often taken as negligible in exams).
  4. Ohm’s law: R = V / I; consequences — for constant p.d., increasing R decreases I; for constant I, increasing R increases p.d.
  5. Worked Example: 12Ω and 0.3A → V = 3.6V.
  6. Extended tier only — I‑V graphs: linear (ohmic) straight line through origin with constant R (wires, fixed resistors at constant temperature).
  7. Non‑linear (non‑ohmic) curves (filament lamp, diode, LDRs, thermistors).
  8. Filament lamp: as current increases, temperature and R increase; S‑shaped curve; flatter slope means higher R (increased lattice vibration impedes electrons).
  9. Diode: conducts in one direction (forward bias) and not in reverse (reverse bias) — I‑V shows sharp increase forward, zero reverse.
  10. Examiner Tips and Tricks: recognise, sketch, explain the three I‑V graphs.

10) Resistance of a Wire

As electrons pass through a wire they collide with metal ions; energy transfers from electrons’ kinetic store to ions; ion vibration (temperature) increases; more collisions → increased resistance.
Longer wire → more collisions → greater resistance.
Thicker wire (greater area) → more space for electrons → smaller resistance.
Extended tier only — R ∝ L and R ∝ 1/A (length and cross‑section relationships).
  1. As electrons pass through a wire they collide with metal ions; energy transfers from electrons’ kinetic store to ions; ion vibration (temperature) increases; more collisions → increased resistance.
  2. Longer wire → more collisions → greater resistance.
  3. Thicker wire (greater area) → more space for electrons → smaller resistance.
  4. Extended tier only — R ∝ L and R ∝ 1/A (length and cross‑section relationships).

11) Electrical Energy

As charge flows, energy is transferred from power source to components; components dissipate energy to surroundings.
Appliances: many transfer energy electrically from mains. With motors (vacuum cleaners, washing machines, refrigerators): energy to kinetic store of motor; with heaters (toasters, kettles, boilers/radiators): energy to thermal store of heating element/system.
Electrical energy equation: E = V I t (E in J).
Worked Example: Washing machine: V = 230V, I = 10.0A, t = 3 h 16 min = 11 760s → E = 27 048 000J ≈ 27MJ.
  1. As charge flows, energy is transferred from power source to components; components dissipate energy to surroundings.
  2. Appliances: many transfer energy electrically from mains. With motors (vacuum cleaners, washing machines, refrigerators): energy to kinetic store of motor; with heaters (toasters, kettles, boilers/radiators): energy to thermal store of heating element/system.
  3. Electrical energy equation: E = V I t (E in J).
  4. Worked Example: Washing machine: V = 230V, I = 10.0A, t = 3 h 16 min = 11 760s → E = 27 048 000J ≈ 27MJ.

Worked Example — Energy used by a washing machine (230V, 10.0A, 3 h 16 min)

  1. Convert time to seconds: 3 h 16 min = 11 760s.
  2. Use E = V I t: E = 230 × 10 × 11 760 = 27 048 000J (≈ 27MJ).

12) Electrical Power

Power is the rate at which energy is transferred by an appliance.
P = E / t and P = W / t (W is work done). Watt (W) = joule per second (J/s).
Power dissipated by a component: P = I V.
Worked Example (series lamps): 150V supply; readings 135V and 15V; required currents both 0.3A; in series same current flows → both lamps light at normal brightness (Option A).
Measuring energy usage: Joules often large for home use.
Energy in kilowatt‑hours (kWh): 1kWh = 3.6 × 10^6J; conversions between J and kWh.
Worked Example: E = 1.2 × 10^9J → 333.3kWh; cost at 14.2 p/kWh → £47.33.
Examiner Tips and Tricks: be comfortable converting between kWh and J; when using power in W, time must be in seconds.
  1. Power is the rate at which energy is transferred by an appliance.
  2. P = E / t and P = W / t (W is work done). Watt (W) = joule per second (J/s).
  3. Power dissipated by a component: P = I V.
  4. Worked Example (series lamps): 150V supply; readings 135V and 15V; required currents both 0.3A; in series same current flows → both lamps light at normal brightness (Option A).
  5. Measuring energy usage: Joules often large for home use.
  6. Energy in kilowatt‑hours (kWh): 1kWh = 3.6 × 10^6J; conversions between J and kWh.
  7. Worked Example: E = 1.2 × 10^9J → 333.3kWh; cost at 14.2 p/kWh → £47.33.
  8. Examiner Tips and Tricks: be comfortable converting between kWh and J; when using power in W, time must be in seconds.

Worked Example — Two lamps in series on 150V supply

  1. Use P = I V → I = P / V.
  2. 41W at 135V gives I = 0.3A; 4.5W at 15V also gives I = 0.3A.
  3. In series the same current flows, so both lamps operate at normal brightness.
